    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-02-05T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-02-05T09:00:00-05:00" n="216"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d216">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/2384</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-02-05T15:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 5, 1916, 3 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 6, 9 a. m.</hi>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3445. Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Morgenthau</persName> yesterday was
                    introduced by me to <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName> and had
                    long talk with him. He also had an interview with <persName corresp="#p_ZAFM1"
                        >Zimmermann</persName> not arranged by me. His report may interest you.
                        <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Morgenthau</persName> tells me that <persName
                        corresp="#p_ZAFM1">Zimmermann</persName> asked him if it was not a fact that
                    the German-Americans in America would rise to rebellion in case of trouble
                    between Germany and America. <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName>
                    said that Germany had never agreed to give up their torpedoing vessels without
                    notice, but had merely stated that orders had been given not to torpedo certain
                    vessels without notice, and that Germany reserved the right to change these
                    orders at any time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
